Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Attorney Laura P. Sette in court.   Defendant Loraine M Lowling Kwiat did not appear.   Court tried to call the defendant but only received voice mail.  Kevin Michael Osborne appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court makes record of previous hearings.  Defendant called into the court at 1:33 pm, makes her appearance.  State advises it is their belief this matter should continue to suspend the case.  Attorney Sette moves to dismiss this case.  Court continues to suspend the proceedings at this time.  Case put in inactive status.  Parties to update the court in 6 months as to the status of this case.  Court will not schedule another hearing at this time.
